<HEADLINE>
<P>
MANDELA SEEKS AFRICAN REBIRTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 South African President Nelson Mandela asked for a renaissance to pull Africa 
from misery to prosperity, but he told African leaders Monday that a new era 
depends on better government. 
</P>
<P>
 The massacres of Rwanda are a "stern and severe rebuke to all of us," Mandela 
declared at a meeting of the Organization of African Unity, its 30th summit and 
the first free of colonial rule and apartheid. 
</P>
<P>
 He attributed much of Africa's woes to its legacy of colonization but said its 
leaders must bear responsibility for bad government. 
</P>
<P>
 South Africa, long banned from world organizations, is now the 53rd OAU 
member. 
</P>
