<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COSTA MESA; MEETING TO ADDRESS COMMUNITY SAFETY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLSON CUMMER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Representatives from the Police Department, school district and the city will 
attend a neighborhood meeting Wednesday organized by a resident of east Costa 
Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
 Patty Baugh, an Albert Place homeowner for seven years, said she has become 
concerned about neighborhood safety. 
</P>
<P>
 "Things have just been changing," Baugh said. "There are extra adults 
wandering the streets in the daytime that weren't there before. I don't know 
where they came from. It makes me nervous." 
</P>
<P>
 Community Relations Officer Sue Crouse, who plans to speak Wednesday about 
crime prevention, said police have not noticed an increase in crime in the east 
side, but vigilance will help keep the neighborhood safe. 
</P>
<P>
 "People are becoming more aware," Crouse said. "I think you're seeing more 
people becoming involved in the neighborhood. Their eyes are opening up, but we 
haven't seen an increase in crime." 
</P>
<P>
 Baugh has invited gang detail officers and Roy Alvarado, a gang prevention 
counselor, to help educate people. 
</P>
<P>
 Baugh serves on the board of directors of the Eastside Homeowners Assn., which 
she said represents about 20,000 homes east of Newport Boulevard and south of 
Mesa Drive. 
</P>
<P>
 Among other things, code enforcement officers will talk about rules governing 
yard sales -- which are sometimes held more often than the two times the city 
allows yearly, Baugh said. 
</P>
<P>
 "Some of these laws and codes aren't enforced, but I think if we bother (city 
workers), then the laws are enforced," Baugh said. 
</P>
<P>
 She praised Mac Bernd, supervisor of the Newport Mesa Unified School District, 
for agreeing to attend, and said she received help from Crouse and other city 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
 Representatives from the Mesa Consolidated Water District, neighborhood watch 
groups, the animal control department and the housing and community development 
department also will appear at the meeting, Baugh said. 
</P>
<P>
 The meeting will be held at 7 p.m. at Kaiser Elementary School, 2130 Santa Ana 
Ave. WILLSON CUMMER 
</P>
</TEXT>
