<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: ADVERTISING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 AT&T Will Drop Ogilvy & Mather: The phone company said it will drop the big 
firm as one of its advertising agencies after International Business Machines 
Corp. decided last month to consolidate all its advertising business -- 
estimated at $500 million worth -- with Ogilvy.In pulling its estimated 
$100-million account, AT&T cited what it called Ogilvy's conflict of interest, 
the New York Times reported. The decision reflects in part the perceived 
convergence of computing and telecommunications. AT&T will split its former 
Ogilvy account among four other agencies: FCB Leber Katz, Ayer Inc., McCann 
Erickson and Young & Rubicam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061494-0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 051312 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
June 14, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
108 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: ECONOMY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Bankruptcy Filings Dip: The number of filings nationwide for the second 
quarter of fiscal 1994 fell slightly to 206,565 from the previous quarter, 
hitting their lowest level since September, 1990, the Administrative Office of 
the U.S. Courts reported.Filings for the period ended March 31 were more than 
16,000 below those for the period a year ago. Non-business filings -- those 
typically filed by consumers -- totaled 192,707, up 90 from the previous 
quarter. Business filings totaled 13,858, or 95 below the first-quarter number. 
The federal court for the Central District of California reported the greatest 
number of filings at 21,511. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
