<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: TECHNOLOGY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 IBM Moves to End 1956 Decree: International Business Machines Corp. filed a 
motion in U.S. District Court in New York seeking to terminate a consent decree 
the company says makes it difficult to compete in the computer services 
business. The decree requires that IBM operate its computer services business 
as a separate subsidiary, which must pay full retail price for computer 
equipment and software it buys from IBM and resells to its customers. In its 
filing, IBM says there have been significant changes in circumstances that 
warrant termination of the decree, and it argues that the decree imposes costly 
inefficiencies on the company and results in the loss of many millions of 
dollars annually in revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
